Add new data for more data aggregation:

  • date
  • day_of_week
  • month
  • ride_length
fullyear$date <- as.Date(fullyear$started_at, format = "%d/%m/%Y") #as.Date coverts to date object
fullyear$day_of_week <- weekdays(fullyear$date) #using weekdays function to convert dates to week 
fullyear$month<-months(fullyear$date)#using months function to convert dates to month 

fullyear$ride_length <- difftime(fullyear$ended_at,fullyear$started_at, units = "mins")#calculated field for length of the ride using difftime function to get the time difference.

Average ride maximum ride and minimum

fullyear_v2 %>%

Step 6: Visualization

total rides

#using ggplot to visualize using column bars
fullyear_v2 %>%
  group_by(member_casual)%>%
  summarise(Duration_Hours=sum(ride_length))%>%
  
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = member_casual, y = Duration_Hours,fill= member_casual)) + #using ggplot to visualize 
  geom_col(position = "dodge")+
  labs(title= "Cyclistic Bike-Share: May2020- April 2020",
  subtitle="Total Rides By Each User: Casual vs Member")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)+ #keeps Y axis coordinates with comma.
  xlab("User Type")+
  ylab("Duration (min)")

###Types of bike used by member and casual users

fullyear_v2 %>%
  group_by(member_casual, rideable_type)%>%
  summarise (num_of_trips=n())%>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = member_casual, y = num_of_trips,fill=rideable_type)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")+
  labs(title= "Cyclistic Bike-Share: May2020- April 2020",
       subtitle="Total Rides By Each User and bike type")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)+
  xlab("User Type")+
  ylab("Number of Riders")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

###rides during the week ####even though member rode more casual rides for longer duration

fullyear_v2%>%
  group_by(member_casual, day_of_week)%>%
  summarise(number_of_rides=n())%>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = day_of_week, y = number_of_rides,fill=member_casual)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")+
  labs(title= "Cyclistic Bike-Share: May2020- April 2020",
       subtitle="Total Rides Throughout The Week")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)+#this code will show the y values with comma 
  xlab("Weeks")+
  ylab("Number of Rides")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'member_casual'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
